WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hi everybody, I'm Christoph and I'm really excited that I get to tell you the story behind Tidy Finance

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:23.000
and why we believe creating educational content that supports both R and Python yields tremendous benefits for researchers, teachers and students.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Our story actually begins in the year of 2015.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Back then, Professor Kemp Harvey, who is a well-known figure in the field of finance, published a quite provocative paper.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
In the abstract of his paper, he stated that most claimed research findings in financial economics are likely false.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:58.000
As you can imagine, this triggered quite a bit of a debate in finance and even the Financial Times reported about it back then.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:13.000
But one of the most important and long-lasting effects this paper had is that top journals introduced code and data sharing policies.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:27.000
So now, as a researcher, when you want to publish a paper, you have to provide your code and at least some mock data and ideally the actual data that is used to create your results.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:35.000
The Journal of Finance was the first journal to implement this because Kemp Harvey was the editor at the time, so this helped a lot.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
But the other journals followed as well in the coming years.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:53.000
One important consequence of these code and data sharing policies was that as young researchers, we kind of faced a hard time.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:06.000
So you see here a picture of my brilliant colleague and co-author and friend Stefan Voigt and me at the time in 2015 when we started our PhD.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
There was hardly any public code or data available.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So this really sucked because we wanted to do empirical work.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.000
So you have to use proprietary data and come up with the code yourself.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
It was really hard to reproduce papers.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:29.000
I mean, obviously, people are not sharing all the artifacts that you need to replicate the results.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.000
It's very hard to do so.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And since we loved working with data, we found ourselves in this well-known position of data scientists that we spend a lot of time preparing data that actually people have already worked with thousands of times.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
We felt like we are reinventing the wheel every time.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
So that was annoying.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And Stefan and I, we had different coping mechanisms with this situation.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.000
I decided to leave academia, actually.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Before I did that, I started writing blog posts.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.000
I figured that's a great opportunity to signal to potential future employers that I know different things.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
I can do asset pricing stuff, for instance.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:26.000
So what I did is I picked up a textbook that is used for teaching all over the world.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And I love the tidyverse. I love R.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So I combined those two and created a series of blog posts where I just tried to reproduce what's happening in the textbook.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
So these are my tidy asset pricing blog posts series that I started in 2020.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And what happened is that over time, people reached out to me thanking me for putting this stuff online.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
They're like, oh, my God, you make my life so much easier.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Thank you for doing that.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And I mean, they were also asking me to do more stuff, obviously.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
But I was really happy to receive that kind of feedback.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
It's like, OK, I mean, people find my stuff, they use it.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
This is great feedback.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Stefan took another route.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
He stayed in academia. He's a brilliant researcher.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
He's a brilliant professor.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
He's at the University of Copenhagen at the moment.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And he created a course.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
The course is called Advanced Empirical Finance Topics and Data Science.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So in this course, he immediately started working with data.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And students, even if they've never programmed before, they write from the beginning, worked with R, analyzed financial data.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
And it was a success. Students loved it.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And he created some lecture notes, used some of my stuff.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:58.000
And at some point, we kind of jokingly said, well, you know, we have so much stuff, we could create a textbook ourselves.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
This is what we did, actually.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So a couple of years ago, we started creating a website to compile all the things that we've worked on.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And at some point, CRC Press reached out to us.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
They discovered our content, said, don't you want to publish with us?

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And we were thrilled. It sounds really exciting to have a book out there that kind of lives in libraries and bookshelves now.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
But it was very important for us to keep the stuff open source.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
I mean, this is why we started with all of this.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:39.000
And CRC Press was very supportive.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
They said, of course, no problem. You can just keep your website as it is.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Just make sure that people cannot download the PDF.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.000
People can still download HTML files and print to PDF.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
But everything's open source online.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And we are really happy that this worked out this way.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
And this is the first point that I want to make in my presentation.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
There are tremendous benefits of this open source educational content.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
First, fairly obvious, everybody can access it.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Wherever you are, regardless of your financial constraints, you can just visit the website, use the stuff.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
That's brilliant.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.000
As an author, it's also great that you can just keep it up to date.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:37.000
I mean, you will immediately, once you send stuff off to the printing press, you will find a mistake like every time.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
But you can just correct it. You can keep a changelog.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
When a new package comes around, you can just update all the relevant chapters.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
You can add new stuff as you go and collect feedback. That's amazing.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And I want to stress this feedback collection very much because readers can actually contribute.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
So we have our book on GitHub so people can create issues.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And it has happened frequently that people raised issues around, oh, are you sure that this is the way to do it?

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Yes, we were most of the time.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
But sometimes they also ask clarifying questions because the text is not clear enough or the code is not clear enough.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Or they come up with new edge cases that we have not thought about yet.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And that's amazing for me as an author to have this kind of feedback.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Last but not least, I want to emphasize that this fits a programmer workflow.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:41.000
I mean, the empirical textbook that I worked with at the beginning picked up the book and I was reading and coding and just figuring out things.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:49.000
And this is obviously not how things work as a programmer.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:58.000
Now, as a next step, I want to show you a typical page in our Tidy Finance book.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.000
Don't focus so much on the details here. It's just it's about the outline.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So on the top of this example, you have Narrative.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So we economists, we love regression models.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.000
So this is an example where there isn't a regression model.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
So we explain the equation, what's happening, what do we want to estimate?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And this is usually where typical textbooks in finance stop.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:30.000
What we do is we talk about the package, why we're using it, what potential alternatives might be.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:45.000
So for each code chunk, we try to provide much more context than just describing what's going to happen next from an empirical perspective.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So second piece, the code chunk.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:56.000
We try to keep code chunks as small as possible to solve a very specific problem.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Not too many things at the same time in a code chunk, which is sometimes challenging.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And we try to keep the object naming and the syntax consistent across all the chapters.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So people should feel familiar with the syntax when they browse through the book.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And here we're just implementing exactly the regression model that we described above and we're using the function that we described.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And as a third part, we have the results.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:39.000
And we, as much as I love GT and GT Extra to create amazing tables,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:46.000
in our book, we wanted to print the results as they are for people who would just copy the code into their console.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:54.000
So we didn't want to put many bells and whistles around it because we want to be easily reproducible.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:06.000
People can just go to a website, copy the stuff that they find interesting and ideally get exactly the same results.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:16.000
And we call this combination of narrative code and results transparent code.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:22.000
And I think there are also a lot of tremendous benefits.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
I've just talked about the reproducibility.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
People can just copy the stuff.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
They can understand what exactly is happening.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.000
We can bridge the gap between theory and applications very easily.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:45.000
We also have a chapter on machine learning where we do a brief introduction and then immediately jump into applying machine learning models.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
And the content is extendable.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:57.000
So when people understand what's happening in a chapter in specific code chunks, they can just copy it, modify it for their specific application.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So what we have often is that people use some of our stuff to write masterpieces.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Some things happened in 2023.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
We were super happy with the content out there.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
We were motivated to create additional stuff.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And some professors already picked up our stuff.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:26.000
But then the University of Cambridge, Mark Zellman from the university approached us and said, guys, we love your content.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:32.000
It's great. But I'm not allowed to teach R. I can put you in the recommended literature, but my students have to use Python.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:38.000
We said, yeah, what are you going to do?

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
Then all of a sudden we receive an email.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Somebody on GitHub said, I translate your book to Python.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
It's like, oh, wow, resist.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
So he started translating the first few chapters.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
He did not exactly reproduce it.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
It was very hard to follow.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
But it's nice if people do that.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
It's a community. I get a community feeling.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And then ChatGPT came along.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
I can write Python code for you.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
So we thought, it's easy. Let's do that.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:14.000
We can do it with the help of ChatGPT.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.000
And it wasn't obviously as easy as we thought.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
So we spent the last year writing the second book.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
And again, fortunately, CLC Press was again very supportive.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
So we pitched them the idea we can we try to translate the stuff to Python.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
We think there is a big demand for this.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And they said, great, send us the completed manuscript in a month.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And we thought this is not going to fly.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So we spent a year on that.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:50.000
But we managed to publish this.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:56.000
And we got another co-author on the book who is a Python expert.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:03.000
Because Stefan and I, we were very much coming from R and loving the tidyverse.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So we needed somebody to discipline us in the sense that we should do stuff that is very common in Python.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.000
That was an interesting experience.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
Now, our website supports both languages.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:28.000
So you can go to tidyfinance.org and choose the R or Python version.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.000
At this stage, I don't want to just talk about benefits.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:40.000
I feel like there's a stronger trade-off here that you have to face when you're creating this type of content.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And one big pro to me is enhanced reproducibility.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.000
I mean, we had our stuff in R and we just reproduced the stuff in Python.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
That's great.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
We found some mistakes, obviously, in the R version.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:05.000
But we now have two consistent versions of the same applications.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
It increases the accessibility.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And now the University of Cambridge, they can use our stuff.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
There's also learning flexibility.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So for instance, Stefan extended his course by telling his students, I'm just teaching these topics.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
You might pick your own programming language.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
So in the same course, you have some people working with R, some with Python.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.000
And they are able to kind of communicate with each other.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:51.000
And they are super happy that they can pick the tool that they find most valuable.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And I want to mention, Pawsyn makes it really easy.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:03.000
We were super grateful that the Quarto team worked on features that we needed to publish the book just as we wrote it.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So we actually sent, we used pre-release versions to get the final version of the book to the printing press.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:17.000
But it's a great support.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:23.000
But the cons are huge, because this type of consistency is quite challenging.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.000
You have a numerical problem, for instance, an optimization problem.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And then you implement it in a different programming language.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
And all of a sudden, you get different results.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.000
So is it the optimizer? Is it the language? Should I make a mistake with the data?

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:45.000
You have to really tinker things until everything works out.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
And that's the most painful part.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
You have now double the code maintenance.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:59.000
So if somebody discovers a potential mistake in your code and you have to correct it, you have to do it twice.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Or another example, I updated the data that we use in the book for another year.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.000
And now instead of looking at 12 chapters, I had to check 24 chapters.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
So that was kind of a painful experience.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
But overall, it's totally worth it for us.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So we're really happy that now we have both R and Python version on the website.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And we are really looking forward to taking this to the next level by creating new content.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So with this, I want to conclude my talk.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:43.000
I hope that our story inspires some of you to make the world a more reproducible place.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
And I think there are three very simple ingredients.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
First, share your code publicly.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
We've heard many stories about blog posts.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
Or you don't necessarily have to write a book.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
So you can collect feedback.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:09.000
Use Quodo because combining narrative code and results like in the same document is just a much better experience than sharing code as a script with your students.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And if you have the capacity to support multiple programming languages, it's also an amazing experience.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
Thank you everybody for your attention.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:27.000
I'm happy to connect via LinkedIn or chat more here at the conference about reproducibility in finance or maybe in your field.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
Thank you, Christoph.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
Thank you.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
So, yeah, we have a couple minutes for some questions.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So we'll see what comes in.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:44.000
But first one, was it hard to format the book for both HTML and for the version sent to the publisher?

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
Did you have to change much?

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
Yeah.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So in LaTeX, there are these style files, CLS, and they are a real pain because there's thousands of lines of code that you somehow have to integrate.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:12.000
And I felt like on some occasions we reached the limits of the Quodo documentation, but eventually it worked out.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.000
So at the end, we arrived really at a...

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:22.000
So we just can compile the same Quodo files and to render it as an HTML and rendered the PDF version of the book.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So that was fine.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Okay.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Glad it worked out.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:33.000
Although you had to create two versions of the same book.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Do you think it would have been easier to teach people to think like a programmer while using R rather than creating an R in Python books?

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
That way it forces them to experiment?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Sorry, can you repeat the first part?

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Sure.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:19:00.000
Although you had to create two versions of the same book, do you think it would have been easier to teach people to think like a programmer while using R rather than creating an R in a Python version?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.000
Well, it sort of happened.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
I mean, we started out with the R version and figured this is it.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
This is what we'll be doing for the rest of our lives.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
But yeah, life changes in unexpected ways.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.000
So I'm curious to see where this goes.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
We had a request to create a Julia translation.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I have some experience with Julia, but I don't think I have the capacity at the moment.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
Well, thankfully it's open source, right?

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
So if anybody else wants one...

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
Exactly.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
Anyone in the crowd?

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:37.000
Yeah, if somebody wants to create a Julia translation, I'm happy to support.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Can you speak to your experience trying to have ChatGPT translate for you?

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
I only have 20 seconds left.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:55.000
So I use ChatGPT in my everyday life now as a coder for also stuff that are too purely in R.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Usually when we translate something, we just ask ChatGPT to translate it.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
So we tried to implement and we tested it and it didn't work out.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.000
So we debug it.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.000
And fortunately we had four co-authors.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:15.000
So basically everybody did the same and we got different responses and somehow we merged everything together.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:24.000
So there were basically no cases where you would just ask ChatGPT to translate it, get the code back and use it.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:30.000
So we always had to clean it up, make it more concise, make it work, something like that.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
So it was still a lot of...

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:41.000
So alluding to Emily's point of using method chaining, this is something that ChatGPT does not use at all.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
And we love it very much because it makes the code more readable.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
Okay, thank you.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.000
Thank you.

